**Category:** Ethics / Political Philosophy / Existentialism
**Abstract:** Comprehensive analysis of Albert Camus's evolving stance on the moral legitimacy of violence, tracing his development from absurdism through his participation in the French Resistance to his final position in The Rebel. Critically examines Camus's ultimate view that violence is both necessary and unjustifiable, arguing this position is inadequate. Proposes that the end sometimes justifies the means, contra both absolute pacifism and unlimited revolutionary violence.
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Major philosophical essay demonstrating Monasterio's engagement with existentialist ethics and the practical problem of violence; shows sophisticated treatment of means-ends reasoning.
